	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">Re-reading this again, this morning, I've stumbled upon the "unfair cost of peridots". Clerics are not the only ones that use this gem, you know. Enchanters use it for Rune, necromancers use it for their higher level pet, and paladins use it for their Symbol as well. Perhaps the gem should be modified for lower level Symbol and such [jumping from jasper right into dots is a rather high jump], but I would think at 65, 210pp for a stack of dots should be nearly astoundingly cheap. Adventures have been notorious for their cash loot and items dropped that are sold rather easily. Imagine casting Virtue, that's 1405hp and 72ac, for just 8g9s2c. Or 9s4c. [Those are the prices of a carnelian and a lapis lazuli, respectively. Numbers are from <a href="http://eqtraders.com" target="_blank">EQ Traders</a>.] That is unrealistic. <br />
<br />
Point: There's a reason why you can't interrupt spells on a mount: you always have to trade-off something to get something. If you don't want to eat the cost of the reagent[s], ask for the reagent[s] or compensation from the person requesting the buff. I've found in the rare situation I run out of dots in a group situation, I have several people throwing stacks at me.<br />
<br />
<b>Edit:</b> Oops! Forgot paladins in the dot list. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="Smile"></font></p>
	
